body: OpenVINO doesn't work in Java in 1.8.0 because it's a shared library and Java only supports CUDA shared libraries in 1.8. Try building master.
Trying. Thanks for the quick response!

i rebuilt with master with the same config and get the following error when loading the jar file during gradle build:

```
ai.onnxruntime.OrtException: Error code - ORT_FAIL - message: SessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_OpenVINO: Failed to load shared library
```

Do we need built shared object from the JNI building pipeline?

That should have worked. Did you clean the build environment first? Also check to see if the open vino execution provider is packaged into the jar. It should have been, but unlike the others that one isn't tested in the Java CI tests so I could have messed the CMake logic up.

I look into the built jar file and here is what I found: 
```
ls onnxruntime-1.9.0/ai/onnxruntime/native/linux-x64/     
libonnxruntime.so                    libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so
libonnxruntime4j_jni.so              libonnxruntime_providers_shared.so
```
Is this expected?

Yeah, those are the necessary libraries. It should have thrown a Java exception if it didn't extract the openvino library, and instead you're getting an error out of ORT itself.

Does OpenVINO work in Python in the same environment? That error could be caused by the `libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so` failing to load a dependent library. If possible can you paste the output of `ldd libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so` from the terminal where you're running java to see if it's finding the right native dependencies.

seems that some dependencies are missing: 
```
ldd ai/onnxruntime/native/linux-x64/libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so 
ldd: warning: you do not have execution permission for `ai/onnxruntime/native/linux-x64/libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so'
        linux-vdso.so.1 =>  (0x00007ffda83dc000)

        libinference_engine_c_api.so => not found
        libonnx_importer.so => not found
        libngraph.so => not found
        libstdc++.so.6 => /lib64/libstdc++.so.6 (0x00007fd090c86000)
        libm.so.6 => /lib64/libm.so.6 (0x00007fd090984000)
        libgcc_s.so.1 => /lib64/libgcc_s.so.1 (0x00007fd09076e000)
        libc.so.6 => /lib64/libc.so.6 (0x00007fd0903a0000)
        /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007fd0911ff000)
```

We have not tried Python Openvino in the same environment yet.

Ok, I think that means you've not fully configured your OpenVINO environment, as it adds a bunch of libraries to your library path which is what ORT's OpenVINO executor is looking for. I think you need to make sure this script is executed in your terminal (https://docs.openvinotoolkit.org/latest/openvino_docs_install_guides_installing_openvino_linux.html#set-the-environment-variables), but I don't have access to an OpenVINO installation to test it with.

Got it. Since we build the JNI with openvino in another container, and the test machine doesn't have OpenVINO setups and shared libraries, that is the reason why it is not working. 

I have a noob question: Is it common practice not to put all the dependent shared object into the native folder in the jar file? Otherwise, we will have a fat executable where we don't need any of the dependencies.

We only put the ort binaries in the jar file. If we shipped the dependent libraries it will massively increase the jar file (e.g. CUDA is hundreds of megabytes), especially as the jars are cross platform so we'd need to put both Windows and Linux CUDA binaries.
Agreed. Will try to configure OpenVINO in the test host machine. Thanks very much!

However when I ran the JMH job with ORT JNI, it gave 
```
[E:onnxruntime:DEFAULT, provider_bridge_ort.cc:944 Get] Failed to load library libonnxruntime_providers_openvino.so with error: libtbb.so.2: cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory

```
libtbb.so.2 is located in `/opt/intel/openvino_2021/deployment_tools/inference_engine/external/tbb/lib/libtbb.so.2`, and the $LD_LIBRARY_PATH also have `/opt/intel/openvino_2021/deployment_tools/inference_engine/external/tbb/lib`.  Do you have any idea on why this is happening?

Maybe we're now on it loading the fourth level dependencies (i.e. one of the OpenVINO libraries depends on tbb). I don't know why it can't find that, maybe someone from the ORT team who works on OpenVINO has a better idea? You could check `libinference_engine.so` etc with `ldd` to see if they have missing dependencies.

This error looks familiar and there was one similar onnxruntime thread with the same issue.

```
Plugin [id: 'com.diffplug.spotless', version: '5.9.0'] was not found in any of the following sources:

- Gradle Core Plugins (plugin is not in 'org.gradle' namespace)
- Plugin Repositories (could not resolve plugin artifact 'com.diffplug.spotless:com.diffplug.spotless.gradle.plugin:5.9.0')
  Searched in the following repositories:
    Gradle Central Plugin Repository
```

@Craigacp Any idea on this error? I have seen you respond to similar thread earlier.

That error is probably because gradle doesn't have the proxy configured. It's failing to find the spotless plugin which does code formatting. As it turns out you don't actually need that to build ORT, so can be commented out if you want to edit the build.gradle, but it does touch a bunch of lines.

Haven't ran into this issue before, I used this docker command to install Gradle in the image:

```
# Install Gradle and setup JAVA_HOME
RUN yum -y install zip
RUN curl -s "https://get.sdkman.io" | bash
RUN source "/root/.sdkman/bin/sdkman-init.sh" && sdk install gradle 7.2
ENV JAVA_HOME=/usr/java/jdk1.8.0_172-amd64
ENV GRADLE_HOME=/root/.sdkman/candidates/gradle/current
ENV PATH=$PATH:$GRADLE_HOME/bin
RUN gradle --version
```
